$CATEGORY: CIT/M2/week-4/4-1-foundation-models-trained-once-at-scale-usable-for-many-task

::q1:: Which statement best describes what makes a foundation model different from the narrow Artificial Intelligence systems that came before it? {
~A narrow AI system and a foundation model are essentially the same thing — both are trained once on large, general-purpose datasets and can then be applied to a wide range of different tasks.#Not quite — narrow AI systems were trained on small, task-specific datasets to do exactly one job, which is the opposite of what this describes.
=A foundation model is trained once on broad, diverse data and can then be applied to many different tasks, whereas a narrow AI system was trained for exactly one specific task.#Correct — this is the defining contrast: one trained model with general capability versus a purpose-built model locked to a single job.
~A foundation model is cheaper and faster to train than a narrow AI system because it is built on simpler rules and requires far less data to reach a useful level of performance on any given task.#Not correct — foundation models require far more data and computing power than the narrow AI systems they replaced; the cost is much higher.
~A foundation model can only handle one type of data such as text, while narrow AI systems were more flexible and could handle images, audio, and other data types within a single system.#Not correct — foundation models can handle text, images, audio, and more; it is the narrow AI systems that were each limited to a single data type or task.
#### Tests LO 1 — defining a foundation model and contrasting it with narrow, task-specific AI (corpus §5.1).
}

::q2:: A technology journalist writes that training a leading foundation model "costs tens of millions of dollars and runs for weeks on thousands of specialised processors." Which aspect of foundation models does this best illustrate? {
~It illustrates that foundation models are retrained from scratch every time a user submits a new request, which is why the cumulative cost across millions of daily interactions becomes so high.#Not correct — the model is trained once; it is not retrained for each user request. That is precisely the economic efficiency of the "trained once" approach.
~It illustrates that foundation models are only useful for one task, so the enormous upfront cost is justified by the depth of specialisation the model achieves in that single narrow area.#Not correct — the high cost produces a general-purpose model useful for many tasks, not a deeply specialised single-task system.
~It illustrates that only government organisations and national research institutes can afford to train foundation models, meaning all commercial Artificial Intelligence products must build their own from scratch.#Not correct — the corpus explains that large technology companies and well-funded research labs train foundation models, and most businesses use already-trained models rather than building their own.
=It illustrates the "at scale" part of "trained once at scale" — the enormous upfront investment in data, computing power, and time that is then shared across all the tasks and users that follow.#Correct — "at scale" refers exactly to this large, expensive, one-time training process whose cost is amortised across many subsequent uses.
#### Tests LO 2 — explaining what "trained once at scale" means and why scale matters (corpus §5.2).
}

::q3:: A student says, "I used the same AI model this morning to summarise a news article and then to translate a sentence from English to Hindi — I did not retrain it between tasks." Which concept from this topic does that experience demonstrate? {
=It demonstrates that a foundation model is "usable for many tasks" — the same trained model can handle very different requests because its broad training produced general-purpose internal representations, not narrow rules for a single job.#Correct — summarising and translating are two distinct tasks performed by the same underlying model, which is exactly what "usable for many tasks" means.
~It demonstrates fine-tuning — the model must have been lightly retrained on translation data in the background between the two requests, because switching between such different tasks smoothly requires task-specific adjustment.#Not correct — the student explicitly said no retraining happened; the ability to switch tasks without retraining is the point of a foundation model's general capability.
~It demonstrates that the model is actually a narrow Artificial Intelligence system, because narrow AI systems were specifically designed to handle two closely related tasks at the same time without any retraining between them.#Not correct — narrow AI systems each handled exactly one task; a model that handles many tasks without retraining is a foundation model, not a narrow AI.
~It demonstrates the knowledge cutoff property of the model — because the training data was frozen at a particular point in time, the model can only answer questions or complete tasks that fall before that historical date.#Not correct — the knowledge cutoff describes what information the model knows, not its ability to perform different types of tasks from a single training run.
#### Tests LO 3 — describing what "usable for many tasks" means with concrete task examples (corpus §5.3).
}

::q4:: Which of the following correctly matches a real-world foundation model to the primary type of input it was designed to handle? {
~Whisper (OpenAI) was trained on text prompts and generates photorealistic images from written descriptions; Stable Diffusion was trained on audio recordings and converts spoken words into written transcripts.#Not correct — Whisper is trained on audio and transcribes speech to text; Stable Diffusion is trained on text-image pairs and generates images from text descriptions. The descriptions here are swapped.
~Llama (Meta AI) is a closed, proprietary model that only large enterprises can licence and deploy; Gemini (Google DeepMind) is a fully open-weights model that any developer can freely download and run locally.#Not correct — the corpus describes Llama as an open-weights model that organisations can download and run on their own infrastructure, while Gemini is Google's proprietary family integrated into Google products.
=Whisper (OpenAI) handles audio and transcribes speech to text; GPT-4o handles text, images, and audio within a single model; Llama (Meta AI) is a text-based open-weights model.#Correct — these three descriptions match the corpus exactly: Whisper on audio, GPT-4o as multimodal, and Llama as an open-weights text foundation model.
~GPT-4o is a text-only model with no image or audio capability, making it suitable only for writing tasks; Claude (Anthropic) is Google DeepMind's safety-focused foundation model built specifically for enterprise search.#Not correct — GPT-4o handles text, images, and audio; Claude is Anthropic's model, not Google's. Gemini is Google DeepMind's foundation model family.
#### Tests LO 4 — identifying real-world foundation models by name and the type of input each handles (corpus §7).
}

::q5:: A foundation model has been set up to act as a customer-service assistant for an airline. A developer explains that they did not retrain the model from scratch — they simply gave it written instructions describing the airline's policies and the tone it should use. Which statement about this situation is most accurate? {
~This is an example of the original training process — the developer retrained the model on the airline's data, which is how the model gained its general language ability in the first place.#Not correct — the original training process is the large, expensive, one-time run on massive data that produced the model's general capability; giving it written instructions afterward is a form of adaptation called prompting, not retraining.
=This is an example of adaptation through prompting — the developer guided the already-trained foundation model for a specific use without changing the underlying model or repeating the expensive original training.#Correct — prompting is one of the adaptation methods described in the corpus; it guides the model's behaviour for a specific task without altering the trained base model or its parameters.
~This is not possible with a foundation model — a model can only be used for customer service if it was specifically trained on customer-service data from the start.#Not correct — a key property of foundation models is that the same trained base can be adapted for many specific applications; a model does not need to be purpose-built for customer service to handle it.
~This shows that adaptation replaces the foundation model — once adapted for the airline, the original general-purpose model no longer exists and must be retrained to do anything else.#Not correct — the corpus is explicit that adaptation sits on top of the foundation model and does not replace it; the trained base stays the same while the adaptation layer changes.
#### Tests LO 5 — explaining the general idea of adaptation without confusing it with the original training process (corpus §5.4).
}
